data.content:
Your test works but uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False." MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Better assertion | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "Expected 3, got 1" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Says "value was null" on failure |

For the "contains exactly one admin" check, you could also use:

```csharp
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
```

This both asserts there's exactly one match **and** returns it for further inspection — cleaner than `Single` + a null check.
